f school shootings in the United States (before 2000)#19th century}}\n\n== 20th century ==\n{{main|List of school shootings in the United States (before 2000)#20th century}}\n\n== 21st century ==\n\n=== 2000s ===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:80px;\"|Date\n! style=\"width:140px;\"|Location\n! style=\"width:40px;\"|Deaths\n! style=\"width:40px;\"|Injuries\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Description\n|-\n|{{dts|February 29, 2000}}\n|{{sort|Flint, Michigan}}\n|1\n|0\n|[[Shooting of Kayla Rolland]]: At Buell Elementary School, \n6-year-old Dedrick Owens fatally shot 6-year-old classmate Kayla Rolland. To date, Owens is the youngest documented school shooter.{{sfn|Davies|2008|p=152}}\n|-\n|{{dts|May 26, 2000}}\n|{{sort|Lake Worth, Florida}}\n|1\n|0\n|13-year-old honor student, [[Nathaniel Brazill]], was sent home for throwing water balloons, but returned to his Lake Worth Middle School with a family pistol. He fatally shot teacher Barry Grunow, a popular teacher, he was Brazill's favorite.{{sfn|Davies|2008|p=152}}{{sfn|Crews|2016|p=6}}\n|-\n|{{dts|June 28, 2000}}\n|{{sort|Seattle, Washington}}\n|2<ref name=\":1\" group=\"n\">Including the suspect or perpetrator</ref>\n|0\n|58-year-old Director of the Division of Pathology of the [[University of Washington Medical Center]], Rodger C. Haggitt, was shot dead by 42-year-old Chinese (Taiwan) emigrant and then U. S. citizen, Jian Chen, who had just completed his second year of forensic pathology residency training and had been notified of his contract non-renewal (which Chen wrote would dishonor his family). Chen then committed suicide.<ref>Olympia Washington newspaper, Morning Olympian, 29 June 2000, page 19 and 1 November 2000, page 19</ref> In 2001 the [[Gastrointestinal pathology#History of the Rodger C. Haggitt Gastrointestinal Pathology Society|Rodger C. Haggitt Gastrointestinal Pathology Society]] was named in memory of Dr. Haggitt.\n|-\n|{{dts|August 28, 2000}}\n|{{sort|Fayetteville, Arkansas}}\n|2<ref name=\":1\" group=\"n\" />\n|0\n|36-year-old James Easton Kelly, a PhD candidate in Comparative Literature at [[University of Arkansas]], killed 67-year-old John R. Locke, the English professor overseeing his coursework. Kelly had been dismissed from this PhD program for lack of progress toward his degree. Kelly shot Locke three times before committing suicide in the director's office, which had been isolated by campus police.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/08/28/national/main228544.shtml |title = U. Arkansas Deaths Murder-Suicide |work = [[CBS News]] |date = August 29, 2000 |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100918115852/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/08/28/national/main228544.shtml |archivedate = September 18, 2010 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|September 26, 2000}}\n|{{sort|New Orleans, Louisiana}}\n|0\n|2\n|13 year-olds Darrel Johnson, and Alfred Anderson were initially charged with attempted first-degree murder in the shooting of 15 year-old William Pennington. Pennington, after being shot, managed to gain control of the gun and shoot Johnson in the back.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.deseretnews.com/article/785108/Wounded-student-shoots-teen-attacker-with-same-gun.html |title = Wounded student shoots teen attacker with same gun |work = [[Associated Press]] (New Orleans, Louisiana) |date = September 27, 2000 |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161129143940/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/785108/Wounded-student-shoots-teen-attacker-with-same-gun.html |archivedate = November 29, 2016 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Charges were later reduced to Aggravated Battery.\n|-\n|{{dts|December 1, 2000}}\n|{{sort|San Diego, California}}\n|0\n|1<ref name=\":1\" group=\"n\" />\n|A 15-year-old [[Serra High School (San Diego, California)|Junipero Serra High School]] student who showed off a handgun on campus and threatened to shoot a classmate, ended up accidentally shooting himself, causing minor injuries.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.berkeleydailyplanet.com/issue/2000-12-06/article/2518 |title = San Diego teen allegedly planned to shoot student |work = [[Berkeley Daily Planet]] (Berkeley, California) |date = December 6, 2000 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|March 5, 2001}}\n|{{sort|Santee, California}}\n|2\n|13\n|[[Charles Andrew Williams|Santana High School shooting]]: 15-year-old student, Charles Andrew Williams, killed two students, 14-year-old Bryan Zuckor, and 15-year-old Randy Gordon, at [[Santana High School]] and wounded thirteen others. He was arrested and convicted of murder and attempted murder. He was sentenced to life with the chance of parole after serving fifty years.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://articles.latimes.com/2001/mar/06/news/mn-33987 |title = Often Ridiculed, the Suspect Said, 'I'll Show You One Day' |work = [[Los Angeles Times]] (Los Angeles, California) |date = March 6, 2001 |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100731085900/http://articles.latimes.com/2001/mar/06/news/mn-33987 |archivedate = July 31, 2010 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|March 7, 2001}}\n|{{sort|Williamsport, Pennsylvania}}\n|0\n|1\n|14-year-old student, Elizabeth Catherine Bush, wounded fellow student Kimberly Marchese in the cafeteria of [[Bishop Neumann High School]].<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/school-prayer-follows-school-shooting/ |title = School prayer follows school shooting |work = [[CBS News]] |date = March 7, 2001 |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160419022747/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/school-prayer-follows-school-shooting/ |archivedate = April 19, 2016 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Bush was released in 2004.<ref>http://www.antidepressantsfacts.com/Elizabeth-Bush-18-released.htm</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|May 16, 2001}}\n|{{sort|Parkland, Washington}}\n|2<ref name=\":1\" group=\"n\" />\n|0\n|40-year-old music instructor and organist James D. Holloway was shot multiple times with a .22-caliber handgun at [[Pacific Lutheran University]] by a 55-year-old man from [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]]. The shooter was not a student or employee of the university and also killed himself. The victim was apparently chosen at random as the shooter had a personal dispute with a different staff member who was not on campus that day.<ref>{{cite news|last1=staff|title=Music Teacher Killed in Random Shooting at PLU|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/article/Music-teacher-killed-in-random-shooting-at-PLU-1054979.php|accessdate=27 January 2018|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|date=16 May 2001}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|March 22, 2001}}\n|{{sort|El Cajon, California}}\n|0\n|5\n|18-year-old former student, Jason Hoffman, opened fire at [[Granite Hills High School (El Cajon, California)|Granite Hills High School]], injuring five people. He was convicted of assault and sentenced to prison, where he committed [[suicide]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/metro/granitehills/20020510-9999_2m10jason.html |title = Granite Hills gunman's kin file claim vs. county, sheriff |work = [[Los Angeles Times]] (Los Angeles, California) |date = May 10, 2002 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131224122239/http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/metro/granitehills/20020510-9999_2m10jason.html |archivedate = December 24, 2013 |df = mdy-all |access-date = December 24, 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|March 30, 2001}}\n|{{sort|Gary, Indiana}}\n|1\n|0\n|17-year-old Donald Ray Burt Jr., fatally shot Neal Boyd, IV with one bullet to the head in a parking lot outside [[Lew Wallace High School]].<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.newson6.com/story/7685186/student-fatally-shot-outside-indiana-high-school |title = Student fatally shot outside Indiana high school |work = [[KOTV-DT]] (Tulsa, Oklahoma) |date = March 31, 2001 |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160311005924/http://www.newson6.com/story/7685186/student-fatally-shot-outside-indiana-high-school |archivedate = March 11, 2016 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Burt was sentenced to 57 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwitimes.com/uncategorized/teen-sentenced-for-murder/article_bd283e35-2db1-5649-8350-56b76074349e.html|title=Teen sentenced for murder|first=BRADLEY COLE Times Staff|last=Writer|website=nwitimes.com|accessdate=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|January 15, 2002}}\n|{{sort|New York City, New York}}\n|0\n|2\n|17-year-old Vincent Rodriguez, wounded two students at [[Martin Luther King, Jr. High School (New York)|Martin Luther King, Jr. High School]] in Manhattan, with a semi-automatic pistol. He was retaliating for the victims having harassed his girlfriend. In February 2003, Rodriguez was sentenced to ten years in prison on charges of assault and attempted assault.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0DEED91338F935A25752C0A9649C8B63 |title = Gunfire Wounds 2 Students Inside a Manhattan High School |work = [[The New York Times]] |date = January 16, 2002 |first = Daniel J. |last = Wakin }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|January 16, 2002}}\n|{{sort|Grundy, Virginia}}\n|3\n|3\n|[[Appalachian School of Law shooting]]: Recently dismissed graduate student, 42-year-old Peter Odighizuwa, killed three at the [[Appalachian School of Law]]. 42-year-old dean Anthony Sutin, and 41-year-old professor Thomas Blackwell were killed along with 33-year-old student, Angela Dales. Three other students were also wounded.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/17/us/3-slain-at-law-school-student-is-held.html |title = 3 Slain at Law School; Student Is Held |work = [[The New York Times]] |date = January 17, 2002 |author = Francilines |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170220053900/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/17/us/3-slain-at-law-school-student-is-held.html |archivedate = February 20, 2017 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> In 2005 Odighizuwa received three life sentences and an additional 28 years without the possibility of parole.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oykqAAAAIBAJ&pg=6633,3227476 |title = Man admits law school slayings to avoid death penalty |work = [[Park City Daily News]], Volume 150, Number 58 (Bowling Green, Kentucky) |date = February 27, 2004 |page = 2A }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|February 20, 2002}}\n|{{sort|Milwaukee, Wisconsin}}\n|1\n|0\n|16-year-old [[Washington High School (Milwaukee)|Washington High School]] student, Joseph Johnson Jr., was killed by Phillip D. Jackson Jr., when violence erupts between rival fans in the parking lot, after a basketball game between [[Harold S. Vincent High School|Vincent High School]].<ref>{{cite news |url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HbcaAAAAIBAJ&pg=4506,8045 |title = Teen killed after basketball game |work = [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] (Milwaukee, Wisconsin) |date = February 21, 2002 |page = 1 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|October 7, 2002}}\n|{{sort|Bowie, Maryland}}\n|0\n|1\n|In the [[Beltway sniper attacks]], one victim of several was 13-year-old Iran Brown, who was wounded as he arrived at Benjamin Tasker Middle School in [[Bowie, Maryland]]. His aunt, a nurse who had just dropped him off, rushed him to a hospital emergency room. Despite serious injuries, Brown survived the attack.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3_IbAAAAIBAJ&pg=6973,5029685 |title = Boy tells sniper jury about getting shot outside of school |work = [[The Dispatch (Lexington)|The Dispatch]] (Lexington, North Carolina) |date = October 30, 2003 |page = 3A |first = James |last = Dao }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6f4QSkXB30AC&printsec=frontcover |title = Crime Classification Manual: A Standard System for Investigating and Classifying Violent Crimes |year = 2006 |first1 = John |last1 = Douglas |first2 = Ann W. |last2 = Burgess |first3 = Allen G. |last3 = Burgess |first4 = Robert K. |last4 = Ressler |publisher = [[John Wiley & Sons]] |location = [[San Francisco, California]] |isbn = 978-0-7879-8642-1 |pages = 455\u2013457}}</ref> The shooters, [[Lee Boyd Malvo]] and [[John Allen Muhammad]], were later convicted of numerous unrelated murders committed during their killing spree. Muhammad was executed in 2009, while Malvo was sentenced to life in prison.\n|-\n|{{dts|October 28, 2002}}\n|{{sort|Tucson, Arizona}}\n|4<ref name=\":1\" group=\"n\" />\n|0\n|Failing nursing college student and [[Gulf War]] veteran, 40-year-old Robert Stewart Flores Jr., killed three assistant professors of nursing at the [[University of Arizona]], 50-year-old Robin Rogers, 44-year-old Cheryl McGaffic, and 45-year-old Barbara Monroe, before turning the gun on himself.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/4-dead-in-univ-of-arizona-shooting/ |title = 4 Dead In Univ. Of Arizona Shooting |work = [[CBS News]] |date = October 29, 2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131214204757/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/4-dead-in-univ-of-arizona-shooting/ |archivedate = December 14, 2013 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|October 29, 2002}}\n|{{sort|Jersey City, New Jersey}}\n|0\n|1\n|A 15-year-old student was shot in the abdomen and wounded inside a basement of [[Lincoln High School (Jersey City, New Jersey)|Lincoln High School]], during an argument with another student. Another 15-year-old student was arrested and charged with attempted murder.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/11/02/nyregion/3-students-hurt-in-shooting-near-jersey-city-school.html |title = 3 Students Hurt in Shooting Near Jersey City School |work = [[The New York Times]] |date = November 2, 2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160720201542/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/11/02/nyregion/3-students-hurt-in-shooting-near-jersey-city-school.html |archivedate = July 20, 2016 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|April 2, 2003}}\n|{{sort|Washington, D.C.}}\n|0\n|1\n|A 10th-grader was shot in 